- Use `@Async` annotation in Spring Boot to perform asynchronous operations.
- Ensure MySQL is running and accessible from your application.
- Configure data source properties in `application.properties` or `application.yml`.
- Example of async method:
  ```java
  @Service
  public class AsyncService {
      @Async
      public void doAsyncTask() {
          // Asynchronous task logic here
      }
  }
  ```
- Enable asynchronous processing by adding `@EnableAsync` to your main application class.
- Use `CompletableFuture` for more complex async operations.
- Ensure MySQL JDBC driver is included in your project dependencies.
- Example of using `CompletableFuture`:
  ```java
  @Service
  public class AsyncService {
      @Async
      public CompletableFuture<String> doAsyncTask() {
          // Asynchronous task logic here
          return CompletableFuture.completedFuture("Task completed");
      }
  }
  ```
- Configure thread pool size in `application.properties` or `application.yml`.
- Example configuration:
  ```properties
  spring.task.execution.pool.core-size=5
  spring.task.execution.pool.max-size=10
  spring.task.execution.pool.queue-capacity=25
  ```
- Use AWS CLI for deploying Spring Boot applications to EC2.
- Install and configure AWS CLI on your machine.
- Deploy application using `aws ec2 run-instances` command with appropriate flags.
